{"parentUuid":"df8340a6-787a-48c0-a7c4-f982718adea0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a5b760f7bd0b5bba3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Dzd5NK3NkafQN1hCHw4zSN","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"on-device AI Apple FoundationModels edge inference 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Introducing Apple’s On-Device and Server Foundation Models - Apple Machine Learning Research\",\"url\":\"https://machinelearning.apple.com/research/introducing-apple-foundation-models\"},{\"title\":\"Updates to Apple’s On-Device and Server Foundation Language Models - Apple Machine Learning Research\",\"url\":\"https://machinelearning.apple.com/research/apple-foundation-models-2025-updates\"},{\"title\":\"Apple's Foundation Models Framework: Run AI On-Device With Just a Few Lines of Swift - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/arshtechpro/apples-foundation-models-framework-run-ai-on-device-with-just-a-few-lines-of-swift-lbp\"},{\"title\":\"On-Device LLMs in 2026: What Changed, What Matters, What's Next - Edge AI and Vision Alliance\",\"url\":\"https://www.edge-ai-vision.com/2026/01/on-device-llms-in-2026-what-changed-what-matters-whats-next/\"},{\"title\":\"Apple Got AI Wrong in Public, but Right at the Edge - d4b\",\"url\":\"https://www.d4b.dev/blog/2026-03-13-apple-got-ai-wrong-in-public-but-right-at-the-edge\"},{\"title\":\"On-Device LLMs: State of the Union, 2026 – Vikas Chandra – AI Research @ Meta\",\"url\":\"https://v-chandra.github.io/on-device-llms/\"},{\"title\":\"Apple’s Foundation Models framework unlocks new intelligent app experiences - Apple\",\"url\":\"https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2025/09/apples-foundation-models-framework-unlocks-new-intelligent-app-experiences/\"},{\"title\":\"Apple's Secret AI Strategy Just Broke Cloud AI\",\"url\":\"https://developer.apple.com/videos/play/wwdc2025/286/\"},{\"title\":\"Edge AI and On-Device AI 2026: The Complete Guide - Calmops\",\"url\":\"https://calmops.com/ai/edge-ai-on-device-ai-2026-complete-guide/\"},{\"title\":\"Apple Core AI: How iOS 27 Signals a New Developer Framework at WWDC 2026 - AppleMagazine\",\"url\":\"https://applemagazine.com/apple-core-ai/\"}]\n\nI've completed a web search for information on on-device AI, Apple FoundationModels, and edge inference in 2026. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Apple's Foundation Models and On-Device AI\n\nApple's on-device model is optimized for efficiency and tailored for Apple silicon, enabling low-latency inference with minimal resource usage, while the server model is designed to deliver high accuracy and scalability for more complex tasks.\n\nFor on-device inference, Apple uses low-bit palletization, a critical optimization technique that achieves the necessary memory, power, and performance requirements. More specifically, the on-device model was compressed to 2 bits per weight using Quantization-Aware-Training with a novel combination of learnable weight clipping and weight initialization.\n\n## Developer Framework Access\n\nWith the release of iOS 26, iPadOS 26, and macOS 26, developers can tap into the on-device large language model at the core of Apple Intelligence through the Foundation Models framework, which allows developers to create intelligence features that protect users' privacy and are available offline, all while using AI inference that is free of cost.\n\n## Edge Inference Trends in 2026\n\nRunning LLMs on phones has moved from novelty to practical engineering due to four reasons: latency, privacy, cost, and availability. The trade-off is clear: frontier reasoning and long conversations still favor the cloud, but daily utility tasks like formatting, light Q&A, and summarization increasingly fit on-device.\n\nThe search results show that 2026 represents a significant inflection point for on-device AI, with Apple leading the charge through its Foundation Models framework and hardware-software integration strategy.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b5eb5619-5c9f-4a46-8fbe-a548a8b0433b","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:19:37.990Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"df8340a6-787a-48c0-a7c4-f982718adea0","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"b5eb5619-5c9f-4a46-8fbe-a548a8b0433b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a5b760f7bd0b5bba3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:WebSearch","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01UYdTWEBCBGbAp5kaY37uuX","toolUseID":"toolu_01UYdTWEBCBGbAp5kaY37uuX","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:19:38.216Z","uuid":"7139ef8a-e807-4e67-9a71-61f651507b4a","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"18af64f8-c116-4bc5-a264-338b3ea68898","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a5b760f7bd0b5bba3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UYdTWEBCBGbAp5kaY37uuX","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AI impact jobs employment 2026 what's actually happening\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"How will Artificial Intelligence Affect Jobs 2026-2030 | Nexford University\",\"url\":\"https://www.nexford.edu/insights/how-will-ai-affect-jobs\"},{\"title\":\"AI is simultaneously aiding and replacing workers, wage data suggest - Dallasfed.org\",\"url\":\"https://www.dallasfed.org/research/economics/2026/0224\"},{\"title\":\"Young workers’ employment drops in occupations with high AI exposure - Dallasfed.org\",\"url\":\"https://www.dallasfed.org/research/economics/2026/0106\"},{\"title\":\"Research: How AI Is Changing the Labor Market\",\"url\":\"https://hbr.org/2026/03/research-how-ai-is-changing-the-labor-market\"},{\"title\":\"New Skills and AI Are Reshaping the Future of Work\",\"url\":\"https://www.imf.org/en/blogs/articles/2026/01/14/new-skills-and-ai-are-reshaping-the-future-of-work\"},{\"title\":\"Research on AI and the labor market is still in the first inning | PIIE\",\"url\":\"https://www.piie.com/blogs/realtime-economics/2026/research-ai-and-labor-market-still-first-inning\"},{\"title\":\"Investors predict AI is coming for labor in 2026 | TechCrunch\",\"url\":\"https://techcrunch.com/2025/12/31/investors-predict-ai-is-coming-for-labor-in-2026/\"},{\"title\":\"How artificial intelligence impacts the US labor market | MIT Sloan\",\"url\":\"https://mitsloan.mit.edu/ideas-made-to-matter/how-artificial-intelligence-impacts-us-labor-market\"},{\"title\":\"AI and Human Jobs in 2026: The Real Impact on Work and the Future | by Abdullah Haroon | Mar, 2026 | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@abdullah.haroon1859/ai-and-human-jobs-in-2026-the-real-impact-on-work-and-the-future-b5f921241b40\"},{\"title\":\"AI will impact jobs in 2026, say 89% of HR leaders: CNBC survey\",\"url\":\"https://www.cnbc.com/2025/11/14/ai-to-impact-89percent-of-jobs-next-year-cnbc-survey-finds.html\"}]\n\nBased on the latest research and data from 2026, here's what's actually happening with AI's impact on jobs and employment:\n\n## The Mixed Reality\n\nAI's impact on the labor market depends on whether the technology automates or augments worker tasks, with early data on employment and wages in AI-affected industries suggesting it may be doing both.\n\n## Job Displacement Numbers\n\nThe World Economic Forum has estimated that artificial intelligence will replace some 85 million jobs by 2026. However, AI and automation are expected to displace about 92 million jobs globally by 2030 while creating 170 million new ones, resulting in a net gain of approximately 78 million jobs worldwide.\n\n## The Young Worker Challenge\n\nThe data shows a clear pattern: Workers age 22 to 25 in the most AI-exposed occupations have experienced a 13 percent decline in employment since 2022. AI may substitute for entry-level workers but augment the efforts of experienced workers. Entry-level jobs have higher exposure to AI, as generative AI adoption reduces entry-level hiring—especially when tasks can be automated.\n\n## The Wage Story\n\nInterestingly, wages are rising in AI-exposed occupations that place a high value on a worker's tacit knowledge and experience. Job postings that include a new skill tend to pay about 3 percent more, with an even greater premium for openings with four or more new skills, paying up to 15 percent more in the United Kingdom and 8.5 percent more in the United States.\n\n## What HR Leaders Expect\n\nMore than two-thirds (67%) of senior human resources executives said AI is currently having an impact on jobs at their firms, defined as having a significant portion of an employee's previous tasks automated or changing the way they work. However, for leaders planning to reduce their workforce, the \"general need to cut costs\" was the only reason cited, rather than efficiency gains from AI.\n\n## The Bottom Line\n\nHigh-skill and low-skill workers tend to gain the most while middle-skill roles, like routine office jobs are being squeezed. The impact is not uniform—it's reshaping work rather than simply eliminating it, but the transition creates significant challenges for workers needing to upgrade their skills.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"aa9fb7e1-d7bf-4d2c-bb71-6c22c9c9b294","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:19:38.216Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"18af64f8-c116-4bc5-a264-338b3ea68898","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
